Nigerian emergency services said on Wednesday that a building collapsed, possibly trapping schoolchildren inside. The Nigerian news station Channels TV reported that a school was located on the top floor of the building, adding it collapsed "with pupils feared killed and others trapped." Over the past five years, more than 170 people have been killed in building collapses in Nigeria. Read more: Africa's self-styled prophets and their 'miracles' What we know so far: 'Parents are anxiously awaiting' DW's West Africa correspondent Fanny Facsar reported that up to 100 people could be trapped inside the building. "Parents are anxiously awaiting news about what has happened to their children," said Facsar. Lagos Governor Akinwunmi Ambode said that "about 25 people" had been rescued, "some already dead." Some children have been rescued from the rubble Building collapses common Nigeria has witnessed scores of deaths over collapsed buildings, especially those built illegally. In 2015, more than 110 people were killed when a six-story building collapsed during a church service. Two years later, another church collapsed in Uyo, killing 60 people. Every evening, DW's editors send out a selection of the day's hard news and quality feature journalism. You can sign up to receive it directly here. Send  Facebook   Twitter   google+   Whatsapp   Tumblr   linkedin   stumble   Digg   reddit   Newsvine Permalink https://p.dw.com/p/34qF5 ls/sms (AFP, Reuters)